Education vs. Obesity Rate¶

Introduction¶

The data science pipeline is the use of technology to analyze large amounts of data and be able to draw conclusions from them. I've always had the question: does education correlate with obesity level? From a common sense viewpoint, it seems like there has to be: that less educated people tend to eat less healthy foods and exercise less, possibly leading to higher rates of obesity. The question is whether that "common sense" hypothesis is supported by the data. I believe it is really important to be able to back up this thinking or have it debunked by the data. I sought to find an answer by using the data science pipeline.

Data Collection¶

I gathered my data from two sources: the CDC's obesity dataset at https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/, and Data.gov's education dataset at https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/choose-maryland-compare-states-education. Both of these are respected government agencies that organize high quality data. I picked these datasets because they contained relevant information that I would need in this analysis.

Let's focus on the obesity data first. The obesity data from the CDC gives us a whole decades worth of yearly obesity values from every state plus DC and a few territories. The education data from from Data.gov gives us a several different metrics of education levels in the 50 states plus DC. I decided I would do this comparison on the state level because that seemed the easiest way to analyze a correlation since the states have large variations in education level and obesity level.

Great! We have the data in a pandas dataframe. The main concern right now is there is a lot of redundant information and the data is organized somewhat poorly. We have rows that have the exact same state, just different years. I would rather organize the entire dataframe by year, and have the states as the columns that are the states. There is a LOT that could be cleaned up here.

The first thing we want to do is pivot the entire table such that the new indicies are the years and the columns are the states. df.pivot_table is a great function to do this.

In [ ]:

We can see there are a number of metrics here that could reflect the "education quality" of a state. For example, money spent on students may reflect the state's efforts to educate students but not reflect an outcome of more educated students. Annual college graduates on its own wouldn't make sense because we have to know the total number of people in a state since bigger states have more graduates, and even then there could be a variety of demographic factors that could sway accuracy of that number. Graduate degree attainment may be a bit too selective in what it means to be "more educated", discounting countless other well educated people. It is very important to think about these questions when choosing data so as to not cloud the results.

I think I'll be testing a few metrics. I'll be testing school expenditures per pupil, high school, and bachelor's degree attainment. We can then make a comparison and see if one of these metrics is more "predictive" of obesity than other ones.

The obesity dataframe we made from before tracks the entire decade from 2010-2020. We don't have year specific data for education, so we need to take either a single year or find the average of each state's obesity rate. I'm going to go for the average.
